1
00:00:04,004 --> 00:00:10,427
NIKO KOBAYASHI - MEMORIAL SERVICE

2
00:00:29,195 --> 00:00:31,990
It's sad to reunite
under these circumstances.

3
00:00:32,615 --> 00:00:34,743
I'm sure he feels the same way too.

4
00:00:38,913 --> 00:00:40,832
Well, I'll be going now.

5
00:00:40,915 --> 00:00:42,751
- Okay.
- Goodbye.

6
00:00:56,389 --> 00:00:57,474
Mr. Yamada.

7
00:00:58,266 --> 00:01:00,226
Thank you for coming today.

8
00:01:00,810 --> 00:01:01,895
Thank you.

9
00:01:02,437 --> 00:01:04,397
Were you aware of it?

10
00:01:07,734 --> 00:01:10,612
Not at all. What about you?

11
00:01:10,695 --> 00:01:12,447
I didn't know either.

12
00:01:12,530 --> 00:01:13,615
- I had no idea.
- Thank you.

13
00:01:13,698 --> 00:01:17,327
But the other day, I invited him out
for drinks and he declined.

14
00:01:17,410 --> 00:01:19,704
So I thought that was unlike him.

15
00:01:26,377 --> 00:01:30,131
Excuse me, are you Ms. Sakura?

16
00:01:30,215 --> 00:01:31,591
Yes.

17
00:01:32,258 --> 00:01:33,927
I'm a big fan of yours.

18
00:01:34,010 --> 00:01:36,846
I didn't know you were also acquainted
with Niko.

19
00:01:37,555 --> 00:01:38,556
Yes.

20
00:01:41,601 --> 00:01:44,103
I knew about his illness.

21
00:01:50,318 --> 00:01:52,487
Do you have plans after this?

22
00:01:52,570 --> 00:01:53,780
I'm meeting someone.

23
00:01:55,115 --> 00:01:56,366
- Okay.
- Yeah.

24
00:01:56,449 --> 00:01:57,617
- See you.
- Bye.

25
00:02:24,769 --> 00:02:28,857
I wonder what it means to be born.

26
00:02:30,316 --> 00:02:31,526
You don't mean death?

27
00:02:32,652 --> 00:02:33,736
No, to be born.

28
00:02:36,781 --> 00:02:37,907
What do you mean?

29
00:02:39,450 --> 00:02:42,787
Well, putting the details of sex aside,

30
00:02:43,663 --> 00:02:49,419
did you know
from a young age how babies are born?

31
00:02:50,086 --> 00:02:50,962
What?

32
00:02:51,963 --> 00:02:56,259
When I was in elementary school,
up until about the third grade,

33
00:02:57,260 --> 00:02:59,178
I thought that the first child

34
00:02:59,262 --> 00:03:02,181
would naturally come into the world

35
00:03:02,265 --> 00:03:03,850
if a father and mother

36
00:03:03,933 --> 00:03:06,769
were married and loved each other.

37
00:03:07,854 --> 00:03:11,649
And from the second child onwards,
I wasn't sure of the specifics,

38
00:03:11,733 --> 00:03:14,861
but I honestly believed
that something naughty

39
00:03:14,944 --> 00:03:19,949
or indecent happened
before they were born.

40
00:03:21,534 --> 00:03:23,703
- How cute.
- Yeah.

41
00:03:24,537 --> 00:03:26,289
So, I have an older sister,

42
00:03:27,165 --> 00:03:28,458
but for a long time

43
00:03:28,541 --> 00:03:30,585
I thought that she was
born out of pure love,

44
00:03:31,252 --> 00:03:33,922
simply because
our parents loved each other.

45
00:03:34,505 --> 00:03:36,424
And that I was

46
00:03:37,467 --> 00:03:40,011
born out of some kind of dirty,

47
00:03:40,094 --> 00:03:43,473
and filthy act.

48
00:03:46,267 --> 00:03:47,477
Did you think anything like that?

49
00:03:49,896 --> 00:03:52,690
In my case,
when I was in elementary school,

50
00:03:52,774 --> 00:03:56,569
I thought that babies were born
by laying down on the same bed.

51
00:03:56,653 --> 00:03:58,780
- That's so funny.
- Yeah.

52
00:04:15,630 --> 00:04:18,508
You lost your dad, right?

53
00:04:19,926 --> 00:04:20,885
Yeah.

54
00:04:22,095 --> 00:04:23,179
I see.

55
00:04:25,682 --> 00:04:26,849
Do you have siblings?

56
00:04:28,142 --> 00:04:29,894
I have one younger brother.

57
00:04:33,314 --> 00:04:36,734
So I was born out of pure love,

58
00:04:36,818 --> 00:04:39,988
and he was born out of something indecent.

59
00:04:40,905 --> 00:04:42,532
Something indecent.

60
00:04:44,325 --> 00:04:45,535
That sounds harsh.

61
00:04:46,911 --> 00:04:48,663
Something indecent.

62
00:04:50,331 --> 00:04:51,833
A catchy Japanese phrase.

63
00:05:02,135 --> 00:05:04,887
I think I'll read Niko Kobayashi's
latest novel.

64
00:05:07,515 --> 00:05:10,685
I read it, but it wasn't that interesting.

65
00:05:11,728 --> 00:05:12,812
You read it, huh?

66
00:05:19,819 --> 00:05:21,362
Do you want to drink something?

67
00:05:22,363 --> 00:05:26,367
Thanks. I'll have tea.

68
00:05:26,451 --> 00:05:27,827
Warm tea?

69
00:05:28,578 --> 00:05:31,331
Whatever is easiest.
Cold barley tea is fine too.

70
00:05:32,540 --> 00:05:34,500
I don't mind boiling water.

71
00:05:35,084 --> 00:05:37,879
No, I prefer something cold.
I'll have barley tea.

72
00:05:39,714 --> 00:05:41,424
You're so weird.

73
00:05:46,554 --> 00:05:48,681
- You know…
- Yeah?

74
00:05:49,891 --> 00:05:53,436
This goes for novels, movies,

75
00:05:54,062 --> 00:05:56,022
and TV dramas too,

76
00:05:58,024 --> 00:06:00,526
but those creative works

77
00:06:01,819 --> 00:06:04,447
steal moments of other people's lives.

78
00:06:05,364 --> 00:06:09,410
Maybe it's more like receiving their time
than stealing.

79
00:06:12,205 --> 00:06:14,290
It's a job I'm grateful for,
but it's scary.

80
00:06:16,375 --> 00:06:19,754
I want to die without having much impact
on people's lives.

81
00:06:25,051 --> 00:06:26,302
I can relate to that.

82
00:06:30,598 --> 00:06:31,724
But…

83
00:06:32,433 --> 00:06:33,309
Yeah?

84
00:06:36,604 --> 00:06:41,484
But I still want to read your latest work.

85
00:06:41,567 --> 00:06:42,652
Here you go.

86
00:06:44,445 --> 00:06:45,571
Thank you.

87
00:06:58,751 --> 00:07:00,086
Before he passed away,

88
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:04,590
the last time I saw Niko,

89
00:07:06,926 --> 00:07:09,053
he asked me
if I had a boyfriend right now.

90
00:07:10,012 --> 00:07:12,098
I told him yes,

91
00:07:12,181 --> 00:07:14,559
and that we were getting along very well.

92
00:07:18,312 --> 00:07:19,439
When

93
00:07:20,606 --> 00:07:23,818
I realized that from Niko's perspective,
I was a happy person,

94
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:26,446
I thought that lying isn't so bad.

95
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,448
I shouldn't say "lying,"

96
00:07:29,449 --> 00:07:30,867
since it's not exactly a lie.

97
00:07:33,411 --> 00:07:37,665
I realized that the truth
isn't always what makes someone happy.

98
00:07:38,875 --> 00:07:40,126
I realized that obvious fact.

99
00:07:42,462 --> 00:07:43,546
Yeah.

100
00:07:46,883 --> 00:07:50,803
That's what novels and other
creative works are to begin with.

101
00:07:52,597 --> 00:07:57,059
They can make people unhappy or happy.

102
00:07:57,143 --> 00:07:58,478
Even with the same book.

103
00:08:05,234 --> 00:08:06,527
This is just me,

104
00:08:08,654 --> 00:08:10,823
but I try not to think about

105
00:08:12,408 --> 00:08:14,827
leaving this world as something sad.

106
00:08:15,912 --> 00:08:16,954
I guess suicide

107
00:08:18,247 --> 00:08:21,167
or accidents are different,
but this is concerning illness.

108
00:08:25,421 --> 00:08:29,091
I think Mr. Kobayashi was happy
that he got to see you.

109
00:08:30,760 --> 00:08:33,012
Not that I know anything
about the two of you.

110
00:08:48,027 --> 00:08:50,196
Niko Kobayashi was happy.

111
00:08:55,409 --> 00:08:57,620
Niko Kobayashi was happy.

112
00:09:02,208 --> 00:09:05,878
Niko Kobayashi is still happy.

113
00:09:28,401 --> 00:09:31,195
Oh, I forgot my boyfriend
is cooking for me today.

114
00:09:37,743 --> 00:09:40,913
He says, "I'm sure you're feeling down,
so let's eat something delicious."

115
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:47,503
He's making me a warm meal since I might
be tired from processing someone's death.

116
00:09:48,504 --> 00:09:50,089
He's making pot-au-feu.

117
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:53,968
Pot-au-feu is the best. It warms you up.

118
00:09:56,429 --> 00:09:59,432
Says Yamada as he takes another sip
of the cold barley tea.

119
00:10:00,433 --> 00:10:01,475
Hey.

120
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:08,816
He's a nice guy.

121
00:10:12,028 --> 00:10:13,112
Yeah, he is.

122
00:10:15,489 --> 00:10:17,867
Ayana Tsuchida was happy.

123
00:10:18,451 --> 00:10:20,161
Hey, I haven't died yet.

124
00:10:23,914 --> 00:10:26,250
Are you getting along well
with your girlfriend?

125
00:10:27,418 --> 00:10:29,837
It's as usual, I guess.

126
00:10:35,551 --> 00:10:38,220
All right. Let's get going.

127
00:11:05,915 --> 00:11:07,166
Coming.

128
00:11:10,378 --> 00:11:11,921
Do you have salt?

129
00:11:12,004 --> 00:11:13,255
Yeah, hold on.

130
00:11:18,844 --> 00:11:20,971
How much am I supposed to sprinkle on?

131
00:11:21,055 --> 00:11:23,182
I think that's good enough.

132
00:11:23,265 --> 00:11:26,268
- Isn't that too much? That's enough.
- Is it too much?

133
00:11:26,352 --> 00:11:29,230
Thanks. I have so much salt on me.

134
00:11:31,023 --> 00:11:32,149
Thanks.

135
00:11:32,233 --> 00:11:33,943
Thanks for cooking for me.

136
00:11:34,026 --> 00:11:35,778
- I'll be done soon.
- Okay.

137
00:11:41,033 --> 00:11:42,243
Are you okay?

138
00:11:42,952 --> 00:11:44,537
Yeah, I'm okay.

139
00:11:53,504 --> 00:11:54,880
You must be tired.

140
00:11:57,091 --> 00:11:58,259
Yeah, I'm tired.

141
00:12:02,805 --> 00:12:05,474
That looks delicious.
It has lots of vegetables.

142
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:06,767
It's really good.

143
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:09,353
It's warm and good for the soul.

144
00:12:13,107 --> 00:12:14,233
You should get changed.

145
00:12:20,030 --> 00:12:22,241
- I want to eat it right now.
- It'll be done soon.

146
00:12:29,123 --> 00:12:30,416
It's so soft.

147
00:12:36,172 --> 00:12:38,299
Did you have much interaction with him?

148
00:12:40,009 --> 00:12:41,218
With Mr. Niko Kobayashi.

149
00:12:42,428 --> 00:12:45,306
- You were reading his novel the other day.
- Yeah.

150
00:12:45,389 --> 00:12:46,307
NIKO KOBAYASHI

151
00:12:46,390 --> 00:12:48,350
Not only did I interact with him,

152
00:12:48,434 --> 00:12:50,352
but he was also a senior at my university.

153
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:51,562
Really?

154
00:12:52,313 --> 00:12:53,481
Yeah.

155
00:12:53,564 --> 00:12:56,317
He's the person who suggested
I write a novel.

156
00:12:56,400 --> 00:12:58,694
You were that close to him?

157
00:13:02,615 --> 00:13:05,576
In fact, we were going out.

158
00:13:07,119 --> 00:13:08,245
Really?

159
00:13:12,917 --> 00:13:15,127
Is it the person you wrote about
in your novel?

160
00:13:15,878 --> 00:13:17,379
That's right. It was based on him.

161
00:13:18,547 --> 00:13:20,966
Although I added
a lot of creative imagination to it too.

162
00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:24,261
- I see.
- Yeah.

163
00:13:27,389 --> 00:13:29,934
Then his death must've affected you a lot.

164
00:13:33,604 --> 00:13:35,147
But you know,

165
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:38,400
it hasn't really hit me yet.

166
00:13:40,903 --> 00:13:42,488
So I'm not that sad.

167
00:13:43,531 --> 00:13:44,657
I see.

168
00:13:56,293 --> 00:13:59,129
Maybe you haven't reached
the level of grief yet.

169
00:14:02,216 --> 00:14:07,096
Grief comes suddenly to some people,
and slowly to others.

170
00:14:07,680 --> 00:14:08,847
Just my guess.

171
00:14:10,558 --> 00:14:14,436
When I see people bawling at funerals,
I sometimes feel a bit put off.

172
00:14:17,982 --> 00:14:19,942
But I do envy them too.

173
00:14:21,861 --> 00:14:22,903
I can relate to that.

174
00:14:38,002 --> 00:14:40,796
I'm sorry for telling you that he was
my ex. Does it bother you?

175
00:14:41,380 --> 00:14:43,340
No, I'm happy that you told me.

176
00:14:44,967 --> 00:14:46,135
Because you

177
00:14:46,886 --> 00:14:49,555
don't usually share important details
about yourself.

178
00:15:04,069 --> 00:15:05,070
Yum.

179
00:15:07,448 --> 00:15:08,449
Yeah, it's good.

180
00:15:50,407 --> 00:15:52,368
How was Mr. Yamada?

181
00:15:53,327 --> 00:15:54,453
What?

182
00:15:54,536 --> 00:15:57,539
You were with him
after Niko Kobayashi's funeral, right?

183
00:15:59,541 --> 00:16:00,626
Kind of.

184
00:16:02,962 --> 00:16:05,881
I hope he didn't seem too unstable.

185
00:16:09,885 --> 00:16:11,303
It wasn't so bad.

186
00:16:12,638 --> 00:16:13,764
Okay.

187
00:16:19,311 --> 00:16:21,939
But in a way,
he's always feeling a little down.

188
00:17:02,396 --> 00:17:03,731
<i>Mr. Yamada is…</i>

189
00:17:06,984 --> 00:17:08,694
Mr. Yamada is

190
00:17:08,777 --> 00:17:12,281
still living life pretending
that his girlfriend is still alive, right?

191
00:17:17,369 --> 00:17:18,454
You know…

192
00:17:20,414 --> 00:17:24,293
Humans can only live
for about 100 years at most.

193
00:17:26,045 --> 00:17:28,797
I mean that physically. The physical body

194
00:17:28,881 --> 00:17:31,759
can only live for about 100 years at most.

195
00:17:34,762 --> 00:17:36,513
But if you're like Mr. Yamada,

196
00:17:37,514 --> 00:17:39,600
and somehow your brain

197
00:17:40,476 --> 00:17:43,312
tricks you into believing that someone
who no longer exists,

198
00:17:43,395 --> 00:17:45,230
and is no longer in this world,

199
00:17:45,856 --> 00:17:48,650
is still alive and well,

200
00:17:50,486 --> 00:17:52,154
then that person

201
00:17:52,237 --> 00:17:55,532
can continue to live
not just for 100 years, but forever.

202
00:17:57,701 --> 00:17:58,911
I guess so.

203
00:18:02,039 --> 00:18:03,499
I don't want that.

204
00:18:07,544 --> 00:18:09,963
You don't want to keep living
in someone's memory?

205
00:18:13,342 --> 00:18:14,760
If I die,

206
00:18:15,677 --> 00:18:18,889
I don't mind remaining in someone's heart
as a memory.

207
00:18:24,645 --> 00:18:26,855
But to be kept alive
as if I never physically died,

208
00:18:27,523 --> 00:18:28,649
doesn't seem right.

209
00:18:39,284 --> 00:18:41,578
Not acknowledging someone's death

210
00:18:42,246 --> 00:18:44,164
is just selfishness
of the one left behind.

211
00:18:49,586 --> 00:18:51,839
No matter how much you love
the other person?

212
00:18:53,507 --> 00:18:54,591
Yeah, because

213
00:18:54,675 --> 00:18:58,053
anyone who falls in love with him will
never have their feelings reciprocated.

214
00:18:59,096 --> 00:19:01,557
And Mr. Yamada has his future
ahead of him too.

215
00:19:03,100 --> 00:19:05,435
Even if feelings are not reciprocated,

216
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:09,565
I don't think it's necessarily a bad thing

217
00:19:10,816 --> 00:19:13,277
to love someone.

218
00:19:20,033 --> 00:19:23,120
Not all love has a happy ending.

219
00:19:24,538 --> 00:19:26,999
But I think when you love someone,

220
00:19:27,624 --> 00:19:32,254
that itself is precious enough.

221
00:19:34,047 --> 00:19:36,466
Although it's painful.

222
00:19:53,525 --> 00:19:55,736
- Long time no see.
- Long time no see.

223
00:19:56,570 --> 00:19:57,905
Your hair grew a little.

224
00:19:59,031 --> 00:20:02,117
Did it? I don't think so.

225
00:20:03,619 --> 00:20:04,912
You cut yours, huh?

226
00:20:05,537 --> 00:20:08,582
- Yup.
- It's short.

227
00:20:09,208 --> 00:20:11,210
- Does it look weird?
- No.

228
00:20:13,170 --> 00:20:14,463
Wanna sit?

229
00:20:20,093 --> 00:20:21,178
- Thanks.
- Sure.

230
00:20:27,601 --> 00:20:28,685
What should we eat?

231
00:20:31,521 --> 00:20:33,232
Maybe Chinese food?

232
00:20:34,191 --> 00:20:35,484
Or pasta.

233
00:20:35,567 --> 00:20:37,986
Chinese food and pasta are two completely
different things.

234
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:39,279
Then pasta.

235
00:20:39,363 --> 00:20:41,490
I feel like either Chinese food
or pasta too.

236
00:20:41,573 --> 00:20:42,824
Right?

237
00:20:42,908 --> 00:20:45,369
- Then should we go to a diner?
- Why a diner?

238
00:20:50,832 --> 00:20:53,085
- Nice shot.
- Thanks.

239
00:20:57,130 --> 00:20:58,799
Not bad!

240
00:20:58,882 --> 00:21:00,592
I think I'm getting better!

241
00:21:01,718 --> 00:21:03,679
All right, let's do this.

242
00:21:09,393 --> 00:21:10,352
Oh.

243
00:21:10,435 --> 00:21:12,062
- Pretty good.
- Not bad.

244
00:21:21,488 --> 00:21:22,781
You know,

245
00:21:24,783 --> 00:21:28,036
after Niko's funeral,
I contacted Mr. Tadashi.

246
00:21:30,664 --> 00:21:32,416
We met for the first time since Christmas.

247
00:21:33,792 --> 00:21:36,378
Is that right? Just the two of you?

248
00:21:37,796 --> 00:21:38,922
Just the two of us.

249
00:21:39,506 --> 00:21:42,843
But, why did you two decide to meet up?

250
00:21:46,138 --> 00:21:47,264
Well…

251
00:21:48,682 --> 00:21:49,850
Not sure exactly why.

252
00:21:54,896 --> 00:21:56,398
We don't know when we'll die, right?

253
00:21:57,441 --> 00:21:59,067
It's kind of like Niko.

254
00:22:02,279 --> 00:22:03,864
Thinking about that

255
00:22:07,451 --> 00:22:09,202
made me think about my life.

256
00:22:11,872 --> 00:22:13,332
I started to wonder

257
00:22:14,333 --> 00:22:18,086
why we're not meeting up when
we're both alive and we like each other.

258
00:22:23,342 --> 00:22:26,803
Even though what we want
from each other is a little different.

259
00:22:32,309 --> 00:22:33,310
But…

260
00:22:34,978 --> 00:22:36,480
You guys still wanted to meet up?

261
00:22:44,196 --> 00:22:45,280
And what happened?

262
00:22:46,239 --> 00:22:47,324
After meeting up?

263
00:22:48,283 --> 00:22:50,410
Yeah, how was it? Did you have fun?

264
00:22:53,163 --> 00:22:54,331
It was fun.

265
00:22:55,791 --> 00:22:58,502
Nothing really progressed or changed.

266
00:23:00,003 --> 00:23:01,922
We said we'd see each other again,

267
00:23:02,756 --> 00:23:04,007
and parted ways.

268
00:23:08,011 --> 00:23:09,346
So you didn't set him free.

269
00:23:11,223 --> 00:23:12,349
No, I did not.

270
00:23:15,769 --> 00:23:19,189
More accurately, I couldn't set him free.

271
00:23:22,150 --> 00:23:25,195
Maybe I was arrogant thinking
that I'd be able to set him free.

272
00:23:26,321 --> 00:23:27,197
What?

273
00:23:28,824 --> 00:23:30,033
Because

274
00:23:31,535 --> 00:23:33,370
he really likes me.

275
00:23:35,705 --> 00:23:36,873
I guess I do too.

276
00:23:41,503 --> 00:23:43,088
I wonder if it's all right like this.

277
00:23:45,382 --> 00:23:46,883
I'm sure it is.

278
00:23:48,677 --> 00:23:49,719
Yeah.

279
00:23:52,639 --> 00:23:55,308
I might be able to make this at home.

280
00:23:55,392 --> 00:23:56,309
Really?

281
00:23:57,811 --> 00:24:03,275
Oh, I booked a hot spring
for your birthday.

282
00:24:03,358 --> 00:24:04,609
- Hot spring?
- Yeah.

283
00:24:05,152 --> 00:24:07,612
- You said you wanted to go.
- I'm so happy.

284
00:24:07,696 --> 00:24:08,530
‪This place.

285
00:24:09,614 --> 00:24:11,408
It looks nice. Where is this?

286
00:24:12,701 --> 00:24:14,452
- Ikaho.
- Ikaho.

287
00:24:15,787 --> 00:24:18,540
- Doesn't it look amazing?
- Yeah.

288
00:24:18,623 --> 00:24:21,501
They serve traditional Japanese
multi-course meals in your room.

289
00:24:22,085 --> 00:24:25,422
With sashimi and tempura and stuff.

290
00:24:25,505 --> 00:24:29,134
- And <i>chawanmushi</i>?
- Yeah, <i>chawanmushi</i> and mini hot pot.

291
00:24:29,217 --> 00:24:32,512
- It's going to be so good.
- Yeah. And…

292
00:24:32,596 --> 00:24:36,057
this is the hot spring.

293
00:24:37,767 --> 00:24:40,437
<i>It's fun being with Yukio.</i>

294
00:24:41,271 --> 00:24:42,397
<i>There's no lie in that.</i>

295
00:24:44,316 --> 00:24:48,695
<i>So why am I betraying Yukio?</i>

296
00:24:48,778 --> 00:24:51,281
- Look at this hot spring.
<i>- Why?</i>

297
00:24:55,827 --> 00:24:57,454
It's nice and warm.

298
00:25:05,921 --> 00:25:08,548
How cute. Hey cutie.

299
00:25:08,632 --> 00:25:10,300
What a good doggie.

300
00:25:10,383 --> 00:25:13,053
- Thank you.
- Good day. Bye.

301
00:25:19,809 --> 00:25:21,019
Stop running away.

302
00:25:25,023 --> 00:25:27,025
Can I ask you a question?

303
00:25:27,108 --> 00:25:29,236
Yeah. What is it?

304
00:25:31,821 --> 00:25:33,949
I have a boyfriend,

305
00:25:34,866 --> 00:25:37,160
but I'm also meeting up with you, right?

306
00:25:39,287 --> 00:25:42,249
And I'm battling feelings of guilt,

307
00:25:43,166 --> 00:25:45,877
and I sometimes
don't understand myself anymore.

308
00:25:49,005 --> 00:25:54,261
I've been telling you about
all of these emotions I'm going through.

309
00:25:58,765 --> 00:26:00,850
These dilemmas that include

310
00:26:02,310 --> 00:26:04,562
my own romantic feelings
and sexual behaviors

311
00:26:05,105 --> 00:26:09,192
are so selfish that I even hesitate
to call them dilemmas.

312
00:26:10,986 --> 00:26:12,904
But the person I want to talk to the most

313
00:26:13,488 --> 00:26:16,741
about all of it
is the boyfriend I'm cheating on.

314
00:26:16,825 --> 00:26:19,536
Have you ever found yourself
in a situation like that?

315
00:26:20,537 --> 00:26:22,872
I know that it's a huge contradiction.

316
00:26:24,332 --> 00:26:28,878
But that's how much
I trust that person's opinions and stuff.

317
00:26:31,923 --> 00:26:33,591
I can understand that.

318
00:26:34,801 --> 00:26:37,929
I wish I could talk to my girlfriend
about my problems too.

319
00:26:46,062 --> 00:26:49,190
I can't just talk to anyone
about this feeling.

320
00:26:50,567 --> 00:26:53,778
No one will understand
such a selfish desire.

321
00:26:55,780 --> 00:26:56,948
Yeah.

322
00:27:02,787 --> 00:27:05,790
I've been wondering for a while

323
00:27:07,500 --> 00:27:09,961
whether it's better
to tell the truth or not.

324
00:27:17,927 --> 00:27:20,847
I can't keep living a lie.

325
00:27:25,226 --> 00:27:26,311
But I don't know

326
00:27:27,312 --> 00:27:29,147
if telling him the truth

327
00:27:30,982 --> 00:27:34,319
would be the best for him.

328
00:27:43,286 --> 00:27:44,579
I'm the worst.

329
00:27:47,916 --> 00:27:49,834
<i>If I were to die tomorrow,</i>

330
00:27:51,544 --> 00:27:54,089
<i>who would I want to spend the time with?</i>

331
00:28:04,516 --> 00:28:05,600
<i>For example,</i>

332
00:28:06,226 --> 00:28:08,686
<i>if you have six months left to live,</i>

333
00:28:08,770 --> 00:28:10,355
<i>you're told to spend it however you like</i>

334
00:28:10,438 --> 00:28:13,316
<i>and meet whoever you want to meet.</i>

335
00:28:14,442 --> 00:28:16,653
<i>But if you have 50 years left to live,</i>

336
00:28:17,445 --> 00:28:19,823
<i>you're told to save money, get married,</i>

337
00:28:20,698 --> 00:28:23,827
<i>and love one person.</i>

338
00:28:25,620 --> 00:28:29,124
<i>I've never been able to accept</i>
<i>that the right way to live</i>

339
00:28:29,833 --> 00:28:33,711
<i>and one's integrity depends on the limit</i>
<i>and the length of your life.</i>

340
00:28:33,795 --> 00:28:35,755
WHY DOES THE RIGHT WAY TO LIVE
AND ONE'S INTEGRITY CHANGE

341
00:28:35,839 --> 00:28:38,299
DEPENDING ON THE AMOUNT
OF TIME REMAINING IN ONE'S LIFE?

342
00:28:55,859 --> 00:28:59,946
BALANCE

343
00:29:05,285 --> 00:29:10,415
OGAWA LAUNDROMAT

344
00:29:32,395 --> 00:29:33,438
Excuse me.

345
00:29:37,609 --> 00:29:38,693
Excuse me.

346
00:29:42,906 --> 00:29:44,616
Yes? I'm sorry.

347
00:29:44,699 --> 00:29:46,201
May I try this on?

348
00:29:46,743 --> 00:29:49,454
Yes, of course.
The fitting room is over there.

349
00:29:59,297 --> 00:30:01,382
It's been a really long time.

350
00:30:02,634 --> 00:30:04,260
What's the matter? Did something happen?

351
00:30:04,344 --> 00:30:05,804
Nothing in particular.

352
00:30:05,887 --> 00:30:08,139
I contacted you because I was wondering
how you're doing.

353
00:30:08,890 --> 00:30:09,891
I see.

354
00:30:18,691 --> 00:30:19,984
What is it?

355
00:30:20,068 --> 00:30:21,611
What's going on?

356
00:30:25,740 --> 00:30:27,951
You want to talk to me
about something, right?

357
00:30:28,827 --> 00:30:29,869
I'm all ears.

358
00:30:35,166 --> 00:30:37,877
Maki,

359
00:30:38,670 --> 00:30:40,338
have you not kept in contact with Ayana

360
00:30:41,005 --> 00:30:42,715
ever since you graduated university?

361
00:30:42,799 --> 00:30:45,927
Yeah, I haven't kept in touch with her.

362
00:30:48,680 --> 00:30:49,639
I see.

363
00:30:49,722 --> 00:30:53,768
- Have you?
- Yeah, and we actually work together.

364
00:30:53,852 --> 00:30:55,144
- Is that right?
- Yeah.

365
00:30:55,728 --> 00:30:57,730
I work full-time, and she works part-time.

366
00:30:58,773 --> 00:31:00,441
Ayana writes novels,

367
00:31:00,525 --> 00:31:01,985
but my workplace is flexible,

368
00:31:02,068 --> 00:31:04,529
so I asked if she wants to work
when she's free.

369
00:31:05,655 --> 00:31:07,574
She writes novels?

370
00:31:07,657 --> 00:31:08,908
So she's a novelist?

371
00:31:09,742 --> 00:31:12,412
- She published two novels already.
- Is it sold at bookstores?

372
00:31:13,121 --> 00:31:15,415
- Yup.
- No way!

373
00:31:15,498 --> 00:31:16,958
She's so amazing.

374
00:31:17,792 --> 00:31:19,502
I'm surprised that you didn't know.

375
00:31:19,586 --> 00:31:21,546
I had no idea.

376
00:31:22,338 --> 00:31:23,506
I'll read it next time.

377
00:31:27,218 --> 00:31:28,219
And?

378
00:31:29,053 --> 00:31:30,054
Yeah?

379
00:31:30,722 --> 00:31:33,558
Today's main topic must be about Ayana.

380
00:31:34,517 --> 00:31:35,852
Excuse me.

381
00:31:35,935 --> 00:31:38,062
Thank you for waiting.
I have one tiramisu.

382
00:31:38,146 --> 00:31:39,147
That would be me.

383
00:31:39,689 --> 00:31:41,608
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

384
00:31:43,902 --> 00:31:46,154
- Here's the French toast.
- Thank you.

385
00:31:46,237 --> 00:31:47,572
Please enjoy.

386
00:31:48,656 --> 00:31:49,532
Here you go.

387
00:31:51,242 --> 00:31:52,535
Thank you.

388
00:31:54,412 --> 00:31:57,165
- Maki, do you have a boyfriend?
- Yeah.

389
00:31:57,248 --> 00:32:00,376
- Steady boyfriend?
- Yeah, I'd say so.

390
00:32:00,460 --> 00:32:02,462
- We've been dating for about three years.
- I see.

391
00:32:05,089 --> 00:32:07,800
What is it?
Is it about Ayana's love troubles?

392
00:32:13,389 --> 00:32:15,391
Well…

393
00:32:17,060 --> 00:32:21,064
Ayana has been feeling down lately.

394
00:32:21,147 --> 00:32:23,316
I mean, she's feeling down,

395
00:32:23,399 --> 00:32:25,735
but more like she's spaced out
and absent-minded.

396
00:32:28,947 --> 00:32:29,906
But

397
00:32:30,490 --> 00:32:33,284
I'm not knowledgeable enough about things
to give advice.

398
00:32:33,910 --> 00:32:35,578
And I don't have much experience in love.

399
00:32:39,290 --> 00:32:40,458
So yeah…

400
00:32:43,169 --> 00:32:44,212
And so…

401
00:32:45,505 --> 00:32:46,756
What is it?

402
00:32:46,839 --> 00:32:49,384
Is she cheating or having an affair
or something?

403
00:32:49,467 --> 00:32:52,178
Well, I don't know the specifics.

404
00:32:53,721 --> 00:32:56,516
But it's complicated, huh?

405
00:33:02,146 --> 00:33:06,609
How did your relationship end?

406
00:33:08,653 --> 00:33:09,737
How did it end?

407
00:33:10,571 --> 00:33:13,282
With that guy I really liked?

408
00:33:13,366 --> 00:33:15,618
- The affair?
- Yup.

409
00:33:17,787 --> 00:33:18,913
How it ended, huh?

410
00:33:25,003 --> 00:33:27,797
That was quite some time ago.

411
00:33:28,423 --> 00:33:29,590
That's true.

412
00:33:30,842 --> 00:33:33,720
Sorry for reminding you of things
you probably don't want to remember.

413
00:33:39,934 --> 00:33:41,185
Let's see…

414
00:33:43,688 --> 00:33:44,564
Oh right.

415
00:33:45,189 --> 00:33:47,900
I wrote a letter. It's coming back to me.

416
00:33:48,818 --> 00:33:50,987
- A letter?
- Yeah.

417
00:33:51,821 --> 00:33:55,199
Things got really complicated
towards the end.

418
00:33:55,283 --> 00:33:59,203
Even though I messaged and called,
I couldn't get my feelings across to him.

419
00:34:00,038 --> 00:34:02,832
Even when we met and talked,
I couldn't get my true feelings out.

420
00:34:03,833 --> 00:34:06,169
So I wrote him a letter.

421
00:34:07,170 --> 00:34:08,087
And then?

422
00:34:09,172 --> 00:34:12,717
Then I got a reply.

423
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:16,804
Then we decided to end it

424
00:34:17,513 --> 00:34:19,432
and stop seeing each other.

425
00:34:19,515 --> 00:34:21,476
Yeah, it's all coming back to me.

426
00:34:22,310 --> 00:34:23,227
I see.

427
00:34:30,902 --> 00:34:32,236
Oh, and you know what?

428
00:34:32,320 --> 00:34:35,531
It all started with the letter from Ayana.

429
00:34:37,075 --> 00:34:38,868
What do you mean?

430
00:34:39,994 --> 00:34:42,830
While I was cleaning my room,
I found a letter.

431
00:34:42,914 --> 00:34:45,708
- It was a letter from Ayana.
- Oh, really?

432
00:34:47,085 --> 00:34:51,798
At that time, Ayana was really angry
about my love life.

433
00:34:52,507 --> 00:34:55,885
And I never listened to her.

434
00:34:59,305 --> 00:35:01,182
I didn't want to hear any of it.

435
00:35:01,265 --> 00:35:03,059
I knew she was right.

436
00:35:03,142 --> 00:35:05,853
But she kept on saying this and that,
and how I needed to stop.

437
00:35:05,937 --> 00:35:07,855
I just wanted her to shut up.

438
00:35:09,232 --> 00:35:12,193
And since I was ignoring her so much,

439
00:35:12,819 --> 00:35:14,821
she wrote me a letter.

440
00:35:15,947 --> 00:35:17,907
Well, the words she wrote

441
00:35:17,990 --> 00:35:20,493
weren't any different
from her usual lectures.

442
00:35:21,119 --> 00:35:22,995
It said, "Break up with him right now."

443
00:35:23,079 --> 00:35:24,705
"There's no future with him."

444
00:35:24,789 --> 00:35:26,582
And "You're a serious-minded girl
at heart."

445
00:35:27,291 --> 00:35:31,170
I could've just torn up the letter
and thrown it away right there and then.

446
00:35:35,800 --> 00:35:38,553
But you know…

447
00:35:40,263 --> 00:35:41,556
there's warmth

448
00:35:42,765 --> 00:35:46,894
to a letter because someone
took the time to write it.

449
00:35:52,984 --> 00:35:55,987
So, writing a letter is a good idea.

450
00:36:02,702 --> 00:36:03,786
Please enjoy.

451
00:36:10,251 --> 00:36:11,335
Do you want to eat this?

452
00:36:11,419 --> 00:36:13,337
- I can?
- Yeah.

453
00:36:13,421 --> 00:36:14,338
Thank you.

454
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:21,554
- It's delicious.
- Right?

455
00:36:21,637 --> 00:36:22,972
This is really good.

456
00:36:26,601 --> 00:36:28,686
I really want to talk about it,

457
00:36:30,313 --> 00:36:32,023
but it's difficult to do so face-to-face.

458
00:36:33,608 --> 00:36:35,109
I see.

459
00:36:35,193 --> 00:36:36,277
How about a letter?

460
00:36:37,153 --> 00:36:38,738
- A letter?
- Yeah.

461
00:36:40,072 --> 00:36:42,200
If it were me, I'd write a letter.

462
00:36:44,118 --> 00:36:45,286
Well,

463
00:36:46,746 --> 00:36:49,290
I met a friend recently who said
that when she didn't know

464
00:36:50,208 --> 00:36:51,709
how to express something,

465
00:36:51,792 --> 00:36:54,795
she wrote a letter
and it helped her sort out her feelings.

466
00:37:01,093 --> 00:37:03,471
Yeah, so I recommend writing a letter.

467
00:37:09,227 --> 00:37:10,436
A letter, huh.

468
00:37:23,491 --> 00:37:26,702
Hop, step, hop.

469
00:37:26,786 --> 00:37:28,120
<i>The next day,</i>

470
00:37:28,829 --> 00:37:31,374
<i>I went to a park</i>
<i>near the publishing company,</i>

471
00:37:32,041 --> 00:37:33,709
<i>and I started writing down words</i>

472
00:37:33,793 --> 00:37:37,463
<i>in my usual notebook,</i>
<i>to draft up a letter.</i>

473
00:37:49,308 --> 00:37:53,646
<i>But every word I wrote felt like a lie,</i>

474
00:37:54,730 --> 00:37:56,857
<i>and I couldn't finish it.</i>

475
00:38:05,825 --> 00:38:09,537
<i>Perhaps this is what Mr. Yamada</i>

476
00:38:10,162 --> 00:38:12,373
<i>is also going through</i>
<i>with his current novel.</i>

477
00:38:14,375 --> 00:38:15,418
<i>If that's the case,</i>

478
00:38:16,252 --> 00:38:18,796
<i>maybe I shouldn't have said,</i>
<i>"I want to read it,"</i>

479
00:38:18,879 --> 00:38:21,215
<i>so casually without much thought.</i>

480
00:38:23,092 --> 00:38:24,677
<i>That's what I realized.</i>

481
00:38:40,776 --> 00:38:43,738
This is a short story.

482
00:38:51,620 --> 00:38:52,455
‪Here it is.

483
00:38:55,374 --> 00:38:56,709
Thank you.

484
00:39:02,006 --> 00:39:04,091
I'll read it right away.

485
00:39:06,761 --> 00:39:12,224
THE TEMPERATURE
SEN YAMADA

486
00:39:28,407 --> 00:39:31,410
<i>"The Temperature. By Sen Yamada."</i>

487
00:39:33,037 --> 00:39:36,207
<i>"That night, I was at a friend's house."</i>

488
00:39:37,208 --> 00:39:41,420
<i>"Or maybe that person wasn't a friend,</i>

489
00:39:41,504 --> 00:39:45,758
<i>but my ex-girlfriend instead."</i>

490
00:39:47,134 --> 00:39:51,514
<i>"All of that is very vague and unclear."</i>

491
00:39:53,891 --> 00:39:57,395
<i>"Currently, she has a boyfriend,</i>

492
00:39:57,478 --> 00:39:59,313
<i>and I have a girlfriend too."</i>

493
00:40:01,732 --> 00:40:04,026
<i>"Suddenly her cell phone rang."</i>

494
00:40:05,945 --> 00:40:08,823
<i>"Instead of stepping out,</i>

495
00:40:08,906 --> 00:40:11,575
<i>she just picks up the phone</i>
<i>and answers the call."</i>

496
00:40:14,161 --> 00:40:16,580
<i>"The call is from her boyfriend,</i>

497
00:40:16,664 --> 00:40:18,999
<i>so I pretend to be calm."</i>

498
00:40:20,292 --> 00:40:23,504
<i>"I stay still, while hiding my emotions."</i>

499
00:40:24,713 --> 00:40:26,132
I'll be going now.

500
00:40:27,800 --> 00:40:30,094
You can stay the night if you want.

501
00:40:30,177 --> 00:40:31,345
I'll leave it up to you.

502
00:40:33,139 --> 00:40:34,515
Then I'll stay a little longer.

503
00:40:36,183 --> 00:40:37,601
I might stay the night.

504
00:40:41,355 --> 00:40:42,523
Here.

505
00:40:43,524 --> 00:40:44,775
Drop them in my mailbox.

506
00:40:45,693 --> 00:40:47,403
- See you next time.
- Okay.

507
00:41:02,334 --> 00:41:05,713
<i>"The next morning, on my way home,</i>

508
00:41:07,548 --> 00:41:10,134
<i>I came across a vending machine</i>

509
00:41:10,217 --> 00:41:12,386
<i>being refilled with drinks</i>

510
00:41:13,095 --> 00:41:16,182
<i>and remembered</i>
<i>that this had happened before."</i>

511
00:41:18,934 --> 00:41:22,229
<i>"At the time, I was with that person,</i>

512
00:41:25,357 --> 00:41:27,318
<i>and in front of us was a father and son,</i>

513
00:41:28,068 --> 00:41:31,405
<i>who were also waiting</i>
<i>for the machine to be refilled."</i>

514
00:41:32,698 --> 00:41:34,366
<i>"The father and son stood there."</i>

515
00:41:35,743 --> 00:41:41,415
<i>"The father seemed to be telling his son</i>
<i>that it would take a while."</i>

516
00:41:42,625 --> 00:41:45,711
<i>"But the child next to him</i>
<i>was intent on waiting</i>

517
00:41:45,794 --> 00:41:47,338
<i>and kept observing."</i>

518
00:41:53,093 --> 00:41:56,263
<i>"Clank. Rattle, rattle."</i>

519
00:41:57,723 --> 00:42:01,477
<i>"Clank. Rattle, rattle."</i>

520
00:42:02,978 --> 00:42:05,314
<i>"The cans descend in a snake-like pattern</i>

521
00:42:05,397 --> 00:42:09,902
<i>from top to bottom</i>
<i>to prevent them from getting damaged."</i>

522
00:42:10,528 --> 00:42:14,782
<i>"That's information I learned somewhere.</i>
<i>I try to imagine the cans descending,</i>

523
00:42:14,865 --> 00:42:16,492
<i>as I listen to the sounds."</i>

524
00:42:18,077 --> 00:42:21,163
<i>"Clank. Rattle, rattle."</i>

525
00:42:22,790 --> 00:42:25,709
<i>"The moment the metallic sounds stop,</i>

526
00:42:25,793 --> 00:42:27,086
<i>the child yells…"</i>

527
00:42:29,755 --> 00:42:30,965
How old are you?

528
00:42:32,591 --> 00:42:34,802
- Me?
- Yeah.

529
00:42:34,885 --> 00:42:37,721
I'm 47 years old.

530
00:42:37,805 --> 00:42:40,349
Wow. You're the same age as Dad.

531
00:42:40,432 --> 00:42:41,684
Is that right?

532
00:42:42,393 --> 00:42:43,561
Just give me one minute.

533
00:42:49,233 --> 00:42:51,026
It'll be ready soon.

534
00:42:55,739 --> 00:42:56,865
All right.

535
00:42:57,491 --> 00:42:59,952
Some of the drinks may still be lukewarm.

536
00:43:00,744 --> 00:43:01,829
Sorry.

537
00:43:02,538 --> 00:43:04,623
Did you hear that? They might be lukewarm.

538
00:43:04,707 --> 00:43:05,916
I want to try drinking it.

539
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:07,960
Really? You're curious now?

540
00:43:08,043 --> 00:43:10,879
It won't be good.
Are you sure you want to try it?

541
00:43:10,963 --> 00:43:11,839
Yeah.

542
00:43:13,674 --> 00:43:16,552
Then let's try it. Which one do you want?

543
00:43:16,635 --> 00:43:19,555
<i>"With his eyes shining brightly,</i>

544
00:43:19,638 --> 00:43:23,601
<i>the child looked forward to the juice</i>
<i>with a special temperature."</i>

545
00:43:24,893 --> 00:43:28,063
<i>"He inserted the coin</i>
<i>he received from his father</i>

546
00:43:28,897 --> 00:43:31,567
<i>and pressed the button for the juice</i>
<i>he had originally chosen,</i>

547
00:43:32,318 --> 00:43:34,820
<i>while saying, 'Toh.'"</i>

548
00:43:35,988 --> 00:43:36,947
Toh.

549
00:43:39,366 --> 00:43:40,618
I'll open it for you.

550
00:43:43,329 --> 00:43:44,371
Here you go.

551
00:43:47,416 --> 00:43:48,792
It tastes gross.

552
00:43:49,877 --> 00:43:51,545
What did I tell you?

553
00:43:52,963 --> 00:43:55,299
- Sorry.
- Not at all.

554
00:43:57,009 --> 00:43:57,843
You live around here?

555
00:43:57,926 --> 00:44:00,554
<i>"Strangers become acquainted</i>
<i>with one another."</i>

556
00:44:08,020 --> 00:44:09,980
Sorry, I'll be done soon.

557
00:44:20,157 --> 00:44:21,033
It's ready.

558
00:44:46,433 --> 00:44:47,559
Whoa, it's hot.

559
00:44:50,312 --> 00:44:52,606
<i>"Heated. Cooled."</i>

560
00:44:53,273 --> 00:44:55,359
<i>"Hot. Cold."</i>

561
00:44:56,610 --> 00:44:58,654
<i>"Even if it's lukewarm and tastes bad,</i>

562
00:45:00,155 --> 00:45:02,950
<i>sometimes it's easier</i>
<i>to breathe that way."</i>

563
00:45:04,493 --> 00:45:07,746
<i>"Once there's a clear distinction,</i>
<i>it will definitely end."</i>

564
00:45:09,081 --> 00:45:11,834
<i>"I'll be sad when it ends."</i>

565
00:45:14,128 --> 00:45:19,383
<i>"I notice that my breathing</i>
<i>is shallower than I thought."</i>

566
00:45:21,343 --> 00:45:23,345
<i>"Before I lose that awareness…</i>

567
00:45:28,225 --> 00:45:30,769
<i>I turn back the way I came."</i>

568
00:45:33,147 --> 00:45:35,607
<i>"I must live."</i>

569
00:45:38,986 --> 00:45:42,906
<i>"I must live."</i>

570
00:45:56,170 --> 00:45:57,337
<i>"You fall in love."</i>

571
00:45:58,755 --> 00:46:00,132
<i>"You fall out of love."</i>

572
00:46:06,722 --> 00:46:08,682
<i>"While you're in love with someone,</i>

573
00:46:09,766 --> 00:46:11,643
<i>you fall in love with someone else."</i>

574
00:46:17,608 --> 00:46:20,068
<i>"Should you only love one person?"</i>

575
00:46:22,070 --> 00:46:23,864
<i>"Yes, just one person is better."</i>

576
00:46:25,407 --> 00:46:26,825
<i>"I want to be that way too."</i>

577
00:46:29,369 --> 00:46:32,748
<i>"What? Am I scared?"</i>

578
00:46:38,295 --> 00:46:39,546
Hey.

579
00:46:42,591 --> 00:46:43,759
Oh.

580
00:46:43,842 --> 00:46:45,886
You don't have to sound so disappointed.

581
00:46:54,937 --> 00:46:57,064
What are you doing here?

582
00:46:59,525 --> 00:47:00,692
Hey!

583
00:47:04,738 --> 00:47:05,739
Hey!

584
00:47:07,407 --> 00:47:08,992
You're going to ignore me?

585
00:47:10,869 --> 00:47:16,959
Hey…

586
00:47:18,085 --> 00:47:20,295
Your eyes will go bad
if you read in the dark.

587
00:47:22,714 --> 00:47:24,174
What are you, my mom?

588
00:47:26,802 --> 00:47:29,221
Do you want to go eat ramen?

589
00:47:33,433 --> 00:47:36,061
Hey! Hey!

590
00:47:37,145 --> 00:47:38,063
Wanna go?

591
00:47:39,815 --> 00:47:40,941
You coming?

592
00:47:43,360 --> 00:47:44,903
Hey.

593
00:47:44,987 --> 00:47:46,238
Thank you for the food.

594
00:47:46,321 --> 00:47:47,781
- Enjoy.
- Thanks.

595
00:48:00,294 --> 00:48:02,045
- Yum!
- Delicious.

596
00:48:02,129 --> 00:48:03,630
Hey, guess what?

597
00:48:04,381 --> 00:48:05,716
My grandchild was born.

598
00:48:07,259 --> 00:48:09,094
You're still in your fifties, right?

599
00:48:09,177 --> 00:48:10,596
I'm 49.

600
00:48:11,972 --> 00:48:13,765
You're a young grandpa.

601
00:48:13,849 --> 00:48:15,767
Is it a boy or a girl?

602
00:48:18,478 --> 00:48:21,732
- A girl. She's so cute.
- Wow.

603
00:48:24,901 --> 00:48:28,405
Then let's hope she doesn't end up
looking like you.

604
00:48:28,488 --> 00:48:29,865
Hey!

605
00:48:29,948 --> 00:48:33,118
What's that supposed to mean?

606
00:48:33,201 --> 00:48:35,370
It's better for her to look like me.

607
00:48:35,454 --> 00:48:37,122
- What's her name?
- What?

608
00:48:37,205 --> 00:48:38,915
What's her name?

609
00:48:38,999 --> 00:48:40,167
Her name is

610
00:48:41,460 --> 00:48:42,336
Kokoro.

611
00:48:43,837 --> 00:48:44,796
It's written in <i>hiragana</i>.

612
00:48:45,881 --> 00:48:47,049
That's a nice name.

613
00:48:47,132 --> 00:48:48,467
- You think so?
- Yeah.

614
00:48:49,051 --> 00:48:50,927
She's so adorable.

615
00:48:54,014 --> 00:48:55,307
You like that name, huh?

616
00:49:03,940 --> 00:49:05,359
- Mr. Yukio.
- Yeah?

617
00:49:06,234 --> 00:49:08,487
Want to go grab a bite to eat?

618
00:49:09,363 --> 00:49:12,824
- What?
- I'll lend an ear, if you'd like.

619
00:49:14,493 --> 00:49:15,535
Lend an ear for what?

620
00:49:23,377 --> 00:49:24,461
I wonder.

621
00:49:31,176 --> 00:49:33,720
I wonder what I'll be able
to draw out of you.

622
00:49:39,559 --> 00:49:43,105
Let's go somewhere to eat.

623
00:49:43,855 --> 00:49:45,857
Hooray.

624
00:50:03,375 --> 00:50:04,459
All right, let's go.

625
00:50:13,093 --> 00:50:16,096
THIS DRAMA IS FICTIONAL

626
00:50:16,179 --> 00:50:17,055
Subtitle translation by: Lili Morita
